<p>\example 
How much charge in coulombs is present in an atom with 1200 free electrons?</p>

<p>\solution <br />
The magnitude of an elementary charge is $1.602\x 10^{-19}\un{C}$. However, since an electron carries a negative charge, every electron has $-1.602\x 10^{-19}\un{C}$. Hence,
\begin{align<em>}
	Q &amp;= nq <br />
	&amp;= (1,200)(-1.602\x 10^{-19}\un{C}) <br />
	&amp;= -1.922 \x 10^{-16}\un{C}		\tagans
\end{align</em>}
% q=n×e=1,200×(-1.602×10^(-19) )
% q=-1.922×〖10〗^(-16)</p>

<p>% Note: the negative (-) sign denotes an electron.</p>

<p>\example
A constant current of 0.6 A passes through a wire. Determine the amount of charge that flowed in  one minute.</p>

<p>\given{
	I &amp;= 0.6\un{A} &amp; <br />
	t &amp;= 1\un{min} = 60\un{sec}
}</p>

<p>\solution <br />
To solve for the current, use equation \ref{eq:current in terms of charge and time},
\begin{align<em>}
	I &amp;= \frac{Q}{t} <br />
	Q &amp;= It <br />
	&amp;= (0.6\un{A})(60\un{sec}) <br />
	&amp;= 36\un{C}		\tagans
\end{align</em>}</p>

<p>\subsection{Current Density}
The \tcA{Current Density} measures the amount of electric current that flows through a unit area (\fref{fig:current density on a cross sectional area}). Current density is a vector quantity, its direction point in the same direction as the current.
Mathematically, the magnitude of the current density is defined as, 
\begin{tcolorbox}[ams align]
	J = \frac{I}{A}
\end{tcolorbox}
\vspace{-2em}
\begin{flalign<em>}
	\text{Where:}\quad J &amp;= \text{current density, [$\mathrm{A/m^2}$]} &amp; <br />
		I &amp;= \text{current, [A]} &amp; <br />
		A &amp;= \text{cross-sectional area of the conductor, [$\mathrm{m^2}$]}
\end{flalign</em>}</p>

<p>\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
